		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Good [3.57]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Kelti&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>You can't report someone who didn't break SOE's rules, rude or not.&nbsp;&nbsp;If you have not actively engaged the mob, he is considered to be available to the first person who attacks him. KS'ing means taking him away from someone actively fighting him, out agroing the previous fighter and doing more damage. <br /><br />That said most people respect camps/camping. But there is also a limit how long you can sit there &quot;waiting&quot; calling it a camp, when not actively fighting. Doing that too long is as rude as not respecting a camp.<br /><br />Training is also not considered against soe's rules unless you intentionally did it.  A monk leading a train to your camp, well off the path to the zone line and fd'ing for instance. A train from a bad pull and running for the zone isn't against soe's rules.  It's polite to announce the train, but I don't think it's required. Especially with different languages, do you know German or Spanish for here comes da train?<br /><br />If the behavior was rude, you can report it to a guild, sometimes that can help.  </p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br />I'm not as think as you drunk I am.<br /><br /><a href="HTTP://www.onthesubjectof.com/newtoons/new.htm" target="akztarg">The latest OnTheSubjectOf</a></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td></tr></table>
