		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Mon, Mar 28th 8:19 PM2005 </span><span class="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=1111838375773093386&num=25&post=1&replyto=1112059136563468719"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1112059136563468719></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span class="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id=Sage>gbaji</span></a><b><span id=Sage><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />9930 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span class="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.02]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>Eh? Not really an issue IMO. As you pointed out, the mobs are FFA since there are tons of them in the area, lots of people hunting them, and no mob is any &quot;better&quot; then any other.<br /><br />The rule for single mobs like that is that the group that agros it, gets it. First in force applies to specific mobs that drop specific items. That really doesn't apply here. Um. Let me be clear. In this case, you had *both*. You were &quot;first in force&quot; since you clearly were capable of killing the mob *and* you had it engaaged. The &quot;first in force&quot; rule is intended to give groups who are on the scene of a named/rare mob first shot at it as long as they are there first with a sufficient force and engage in a reasonable amount of time. It's pointless when it comes to general mob killing since every mob in the area applies (although most players will still recognize a group &quot;in force&quot; at a specific camp or group of spawns even though it's not required by the rules). The first in force rule is not intended to be some additional requirement for groups/raids, but an alternative method of establishing &quot;ownership&quot; of a mob. Normal rules say engagement gives you ownership. The problem is that raid forces generally need a bit of prep time and there were issues with folks jumping raids. Some raid groups would respond to this by kiting a mob around until they finished assembling and/or prepping, but then this got abused, so the first in force rule came into being to prevent it. It should never be applied to random mobs in an area.<br /><br /><br /><br />Long ago I got in the habit of /assisting mobs prior to pulling them (especially if they were moving or we were anywhere near other people). My thinking is that if the mob is argoed on someone, my /assist will target that person. If the mob doesn't have anyone targeted, then it's free to pull.<br /><br />Looks like that guy will have to learn that lesson. He certainly should not have been pissed at you (and you should not have been so at him either). It's not uncommon at all to see the mob, but not the other group of PCs hunting the mob. Mistakes happen. I find it's best to just shrug them off and move on. There's plenty of mobs and camps in the game.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
